What is proper info in HINFO records? 

[from RFC 1035]
&gt; 3.3.2. HINFO RDATA format
&gt; 
&gt;     +--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+
&gt;     /                      CPU                      /
&gt;     +--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+
&gt;     /                       OS                      /
&gt;     +--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+--+
&gt; 
&gt; where:
&gt; 
&gt; CPU             A &lt;character-string&gt; which specifies the CPU type.
&gt; 
&gt; OS              A &lt;character-string&gt; which specifies the operating
&gt;                 system type.
&gt; 
&gt; Standard values for CPU and OS can be found in [RFC-1010].

Does this imply that "standard" values must be used?  If so,
what do you do with systems that are not listed in 1010?
(Should I get our home-brewed CPU/OS types added?)

&gt; HINFO records are used to acquire general information about a host.

I consider the main use is to provided up-to-date
hardware/software info to network managers.  When I first read
that there were standard values, I said, "Great, let's use 'em!".
But then I looked at RFC-1010; many (most) of our CPU and OS types
are not listed and there are few generic types.

&gt; The main use is for protocols such as FTP that can use special procedures
&gt; when talking between machines or operating systems of the same type.

-- 
	kurt (zeilenga@hc.dspo.gov)

